    <text>
        <body>
            <div>
                <head>
                    <figure>
                        <graphic url="abu_dhabi_1.jpg" type="thumbnail" />
                        <head type="imgCaption">Courtesy of Stephanie Sarg</head>
                    </figure>
                </head>
                <div type="typology">
                    <p>East (Mashriq) › Arabia › Northern group › Central Najd › Gulf</p>
                    <p>Originally a bedouin-type dialect belonging to the ˁAnaza group; during the last
                  decades in a state of transition</p>
                </div>
                <div type="general">
                    <p>Abu Dhabi is the capital of the United Arab Emirates and its second largest city.
                  Until the mid-20th century Abu Dhabi was a small town of less than 25,000
                  inhabitants, but has grown rapidly in the following decades reaching one million
                  in the early 2000s. However, only a small proportion of its inhabitants are native
                  speakers of the local Arabic dialect. </p>
                </div>
                <div type="researchHistory">
                    <p>
                        <rs type="bibl" ref="zot:johnstone_1967_0000">Johnstone (1967)</rs> presents an overview of
                  the Eastern Arabian dialects in general, but also contains several pages devoted
                  to the dialect of Abu Dhabi.</p>
                        <p>The sound change from /ǧ/ to /y/, which is typical for Gulf Arabic, is described
                  in <rs type="bibl" ref="zot:johnstone_1965_3209">Johnstone (1965)</rs>. <rs type="bibl" ref="zot:qafisheh_1977_3210">Qafisheh (1977)</rs> is based on the dialect of Abu Dhabi
                  and comprises in addition to phonology, morphology and syntax also texts. </p>
                        <p>The focus of <rs type="bibl" ref="zot:al-rawi_1990_3236">Al-Rawi’s study (1990)</rs> is
                  on phonology and nominal morphology; it also contains a number of ethnographic
                  texts. Some information on Abu Dhabi is also found in <rs type="bibl" ref="zot:holes_1990_0000">Holes 1990</rs>.</p>
                    </div>
                    <div type="textBooks">
                        <p>Based on the speech of Abu Dhabi, Qatar and Bahrain, Hamdi A. Qafisheh published
                  three textbooks of Gulf Arabic. <rs type="bibl" ref="zot:qafisheh_1975_0000">Qafisheh
                     1975</rs> for beginners, <rs type="bibl" ref="zot:qafisheh_1979_3235">Qafisheh
                     1979</rs> and <rs type="bibl" ref="zot:qafisheh_1997_0000">Qafisheh 1997</rs> for
                  advanced students. Another textbook is <rs type="bibl" ref="zot:holes_1984_0001">Holes
                     1984</rs>.</p>
                    </div>
                    <div type="bibliography">
                        <p>To view publications on this variety click <rs type="bibl" ref="bibl:geo:Abu Dhabi">here</rs>.</p>
                    </div>
                </div>
